  <li id="comment-30056" class="comment odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1">
    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn"><a href="https://www.blogger.com/profile/01493708300940204826" class="url" rel="ugc external nofollow">Molly</a></cite></div>
      <a href="https://orangette.net/2011/07/you-dont-forget/#comment-30056"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2011-07-20T22:23:40-04:00">Wednesday, July 20, 2011 at 10:23 pm</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>Hi, friends.</p>
<p>Martina, I would trade with you, but I only have one jar left!  Think I&#39;ve got to keep it&#8230;</p>
<p>Jenny, nope, you don&#39;t need to sterilize the jars.  You would only need to do that if you were going to can this, and I&#39;m not sure that this recipe has enough sugar to make it safe for canning and long-term storage.  As it is, though, no need to sterilize.  It&#39;ll be fine to sit in the fridge for a month or so.</p>
<p>M. Larson, re: canning, I wish I could help, but I&#39;m not sure.  (See my reply to Annie, above.  It&#39;s the 7th comment from the top.)</p>
<p>Luckwagon, I think it would work nicely with cherries!  You might need to tweak the sugar a bit.</p>
<p>Kristin, I imagine it would work with sliced peaches, though I haven&#39;t tried&#8230;</p>
    </div>

